    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-07-24T13:44:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-07-24T13:44:00-05:00" n="507"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d507">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.20/603: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hibbard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-07-24T18:00:00-00:44"
                            >July 24, 1942—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 28—1:18 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>243. A British naval lieutenant from Freetown called on Colonel Wood<note n="59"
                        xml:id="d507fn59">Commanding Officer, United States Forces in
                        Liberia.</note> yesterday to ask when the barracks, mess hall and equipment
                        <pb facs="0424" n="412" xml:id="pg_412"/> and other installations would be
                    ready for 3 officers and 15 men which the British wish to send to Cape Palmas
                    for radio work in protecting the coast. I asked Colonel Wood to tell him that so
                    far the United States had no defense at Cape Palmas included in the agreement
                    between the two Governments and that consequently no installation of any kind
                    was contemplated there at present. He was much surprised as he felt from his
                    instructions that the entire matter had been arranged in Washington. If the War
                    Department wishes a defense area at Cape Palmas I am sure the President will
                    grant permission as soon as he has been informed of the location desired. He
                    will not, however, permit the British to install a radio station there until we
                    have taken over the area.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hibbard</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
